{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8ec37c60-d165-48f3-b0fb-c58fdfb2d3d7","content":"Here's the diagnosis and recommendation:\n\n**Root Cause:** Visual Studio keeps a long-running MSBuild server process in memory, so project evaluation is cached across builds. The `dotnet build` CLI spawns a fresh MSBuild process every time, paying startup + evaluation costs (~2-4s) even when nothing changed.\n\n**Recommendations (most to least impactful):**\n\n1. **Use `dotnet watch build`** for the inner loop — it keeps MSBuild in memory and rebuilds incrementally on file changes, eliminating process startup overhead entirely.\n\n2. **Enable MSBuild node reuse** — the CLI defaults to `/nodeReuse:false` (unlike VS). Keeping worker nodes alive between builds avoids re-evaluation:\n\n   ```bash\n   # Set in your shell profile (.bashrc / .zshrc / PowerShell profile)\n   export MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0\n   ```\n\n   Or add to the project/`Directory.Build.props`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <MSBuildNodeReuse>true</MSBuildNodeReuse>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n3. **Enable the MSBuild Server** (opt-in, .NET 8+) — a persistent build server similar to what VS uses:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n   ```\n\n**No changes needed to the `.csproj` itself** — the project is clean. The bottleneck is entirely in CLI process startup/teardown, not in compilation or targets. For quick edit-build-test cycles, `dotnet watch build` is the single biggest win.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8fe8b0d5-8fa4-4995-ac9a-c2f0b381dc08","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses MSBuild Server (a long-running MSBuild process) that keeps the project graph in memory, avoiding the startup and re-evaluation overhead on every build. The CLI, by default, starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThe solution is to use the **MSBuild Server** (`-nodeReuse:true` is related but not the same). Starting with .NET 8 / MSBuild 17.9+, there's an environment variable `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or the property `MSBuildServer` that enables a long-running MSBuild server process for CLI builds, similar to what VS does.\n \nThere are a few different approaches to speed this up: `dotnet build-server` manages the build server lifecycle, `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` enables server reuse, `-nodeReuse:true` keeps worker nodes alive between builds, and `dotnet watch build` keeps the entire process running and only rebuilds on file changes. The most practical recommendation is using `dotnet watch build` since it maintains MSBuild in memory and only triggers rebuilds when source files actually change.\n\nFor the MSBuild Server specifically, I should verify what's actually available in .NET 8 — the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable was experimental and may have changed, but node reuse with the `/nr:true` flag is a reliable way to keep MSBuild worker nodes alive between invocations. alive between builds. By default, CLI sets this to false (unlike VS which sets it to true).\n\nActually, the key difference between VS and CLI:\n1. VS uses a long-running MSBuild server that keeps project evaluation cached in memory\n2. CLI spawns a new `dotnet build` process each time, which re-evaluates the project graph\n\nThe main recommendations for the .csproj and workflow:\n\n1. **Use `dotnet watch build`** for the inner loop - avoids process startup overhead\n2. **Enable MSBuild node reuse** by setting environment variable `MSBuildNodeReuse=1` or `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0` \n3. **Use the MSBuild build server** via `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`\n\nFor .NET 8 specifically, the most practical approach is using `dotnet watch build` for iterative development, and enabling node reuse either through an environment variable or by adding a project property to keep the MSBuild process alive between builds rather than spawning a fresh one each time.","outputTokens":1421,"requestId":"27CC:2346F7:5E02306:656D5C8:69FBE1DC"},"id":"2c55fc5f-de49-45cf-97f3-846a881b8c0a","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:51:07.686Z","parentId":"446c2951-0d1f-469e-8964-293246367cbd"}
